# What is the Hypernet? {#what-is-the-hypernet?}

The Hypernet is The Singularity.  A single location to store all information in the world, into a simple, easy to use database.  It reduces information down to the simplest building blocks.  It is organized much like the human brain, and it simplifies data into its smallest component data parts and links between those data objects.  It then organizes all the information into a massive library, where all data has a unique call number, just like a library, allowing people to not only do keyword searches, but also to browse to subjects, and browse through information as they would in a library.  It will be designed from the ground up to be a true 3D database allowing for new interfaces currently only possible in sci-fi.  It will be even more revolutionary that Graphical User Interfaces that Microsoft developed with Windows.

  In these next sections, we’ll go over the 3 basic components of the Hypernet.  The Library, Objects, and Links.

## The Library {#the-library}

The Library is the structural underpinnings of the Hypernet and how information is organized.  Just like a normal library, it will use a system of topic.subtopic.etc   A significant part of its numbering system, will be pulled from the current library systems method of organization, although it will expand on it significantly to allow it to catalog people, devices, objects, businesses, and more.  The library is infinitely expandable, and categories can be added for any future types of information easily.

The Library is important to one of the biggest strengths of the Hypernet.  It allows for complete deduplication of data.  Every document, picture, or piece of information will have one single location with a unique address.  This will allow the Hypernet to be the most space efficient databases on the planet.

There are a number of important parts of the library that will be addressed later in this document, including the “.0” format that defines and allows standardization of all types of data, the object and link definitions section, and the organization of how servers work together as a cohesive unit to work together as a single entity.

## Objects {#objects}

An object is just what it sounds like.  It is the smallest representation of data and represents a single idea, concept, person, device, object, photo, document, etc.  It is like a neuron in the human brain.  Every object is clearly defined by its type.  And object is stored as a single entity in the Hypernet and contains the following 3 parts:

### Generalized Metadata {#generalized-metadata}

All objects will contain a common set of metadata, including Hypernet Address, Object Type, Creator, Create Date, Last Modified Date, Geographical Location, 2d graphic, 3d graphic, keywords/hashtags and more.  Every object will have the common set of metadata.

### Specialized Metadata {#specialized-metadata}

The specialized metadata will be specific to the object type.  Photos, movies, devices, documents, and more, will all have specific metadata related to the type of information that it contains.

### Payload {#payload}

The payload is the raw information contained in that datatype.  For a photo, it would be the actual photo.  For a movie or video, it would be that movie or video.

### Reasoning behind this organizational layout {#reasoning-behind-this-organizational-layout}

Organizing information in this way gives us some significant advantages.  It allows the Hypernet to do far more advanced searches of information using a Standardized Query Language (SQL).  It allows searches and displaying of data in unique ways.  For example, if you wanted to create a representation of a car, you could create a single multi-object (which will be discussed later), that contains a list of every part that makes up that car and arrange them into a 3d construct of the car.  By querying for the 3d graphic of each object and putting them into a 3d space that represents the car, you could build an entire vehicle with every component of the car down to the last nut and bolt into a 3d space that could be easily manipulated.  It would be easy to zoom into any part of the car, select any component, and get detailed information about any aspect one wished.

This method of organizing data into organized, documented, specific pieces of data creates a “Lego brick” of information allowing you to stack or combine ALL types of information into a single document and allowing information to be combined in ways never seen before.

## Links {#links}

A link is like the axons and dendrites between neurons in the brain.  They are links between objects and are the key to the power of the Hypernet and the reusability of data.

Like Objects, each type of Link is clearly defined and has common and specialized metadata.  Unlike Objects, there is no payload.  Unlike Objects, links are broken into two parts.  The primary half, and the secondary half.  Each half is attached to the two objects that they are linking together, with the primary half containing the majority of metadata, and the secondary half containing the minimum needed for efficiency, with a pointer to the primary half to obtain everything else.

### How Links optimize data. {#how-links-optimize-data.}

Links allow data to be reused in the most efficient possible way.  By searching data using a combination of objects and links, one can combine data in ways never before imagined.

As a basic example, I’ll use people.  Imagine that you have a large number of people with all of their information entered into the Hypernet.  Name, address, phone number, etc.  Everything about them.

### Users and Aliases {#users-and-aliases}

Although this paper will not address the full scale of user profiles and aliases, I do want to address the basics.

#### *Users*

The User objects will be one of the most advanced and complicated in the system.  We want to create an environment where people can store ALL of their personal information.  There will be places to store documents, multi-media, medical history, DNA and biometric information, and more.

On the Hypernet, there will be a VERY strict one account per person rule that will be enforced draconianly.  Because of a robust alias system, additional accounts aren’t needed.  In addition, the reputation system, this is essential for the integrity of the system.  This will be enforced using personal referrals, biometrics, government IDs, or other methods.

In the Hypernet, personal user accounts will be the most protected of all information.  No one, including myself, as the owner of the company, will have access to user accounts.  All user accounts will be treated equally, from the top of the company to the average person.  Personal data protection will be one of the primary focuses.  The Hypernet is most powerful when people can trust it and feel safe loading all their personal information into it.  Although this document will not go into details, personal data will be the most respected and protected data on the Hypernet.

And although I would like to describe all the possibilities that this will provide, it’s too much for this document.  It will allow people to store all of their personal information and keep track of it and use it in mind blowing ways. ##### Lockers/Mandalas

One of the biggest strengths of the Hypernet user profiles is giving users complete control over what information they share with others.  It will allow them to create “lockers” that contain specific types of information that they share.  They can create as many “lockers” as they want, and each one contains only the information they want to share.  For example, someone could create a “Billing” locker that contains their name, address, phone number, etc.  Everything that you might need to provide to your phone company, utilities, credit cards, etc.  When you apply for a credit card, add a utility to your home, apply for a credit card or mortgage, you would simply provide the company with the Mandala (or key) to that locker, and they company would have all the information they need at their fingertips.  If your phone number or address changes, you don’t need to notify dozens of different companies that your address changed, because they have the Mandala for that information, they are automatically updated in real-time about your status change, because that information is linked to your personal profile rather than stored in their personal database.  All information is live and real-time.  This would make applying for jobs, credit cards, mortgages a far simpler process, because you would simply give them the proper Mandala for the information they need, and you would never need to fill out another form for personal access again in your life.

##### Aliases.

To overcome the objections to a one-account per person, the Hypernet will have an alias system.  Users can have as many aliases as they want.  An alias is a mirror of a user account.  One can either link information directly from the primary account, or one could just write whatever one wished.  A direct link would be color coded to show it’s accurate, while other information would be color coded differently.

How this would work.  If one wanted to create a profile for dating sites.  A person may not want to share their name, address, and other information that would put them at risk, so they could make up that information.  But they could link their sex, age, marital status, profession, or whatever they wished.  Their “dating alias” then could allow them to create a fake name, but still validate to others your marital status, age, sex, and more, while still keeping hidden information that might compromise your physical safety.

##### Reputation System

The reputation system is one of the most important, yet controversial aspects of the Hypernet.  It’s something I wish I didn’t need to create, yet the power of the Hypernet makes it inevitable, and if I don’t do it, someone else will, and they won’t do it as well.  So the entire reputation system is something created out of necessity, solely for the purpose of making sure that it’s done properly.

Essentially the reputation system is a measure of a person’s knowledge and character.  In some ways it’s like LinkedIn trying to measure a person’s technical skills, but in other ways it tries to measure a person’s character and who they are as a person.

This will be one of the most controversial aspects of the Hypernet, yet one of the most critical.  One that I wish I didn’t need to create, yet it is vital to it’s success and the democratic system it wants to create.

There are two parts to the reputation system.  Knowledge based reputation, and character-based reputation.

###### Knowledge based Reputation

Knowledge based reputation will be an attempt to understand a person and what their levels of knowledge are in any area.  It will assign points based on what information the user browses on the Hypernet, along with personal recommendations of professionals to try to create a profile to understand exactly how informed a person is about any particular subject.

###### Character based reputation

This will be one of the most controversial, yet important parts of the reputation system.  Like the knowledge-based side, it will try to determine the character of a person based on their interactions with others.  It will be like an “online review” of a person, rather than a product.  It will allow a person’s honest or dishonest actions to follow them through their lifetime (with an algorithm that favors a persons desire to change, over holding past mistakes over them forever.

This will be very controversial and will have some of the most serious checks and balances in the system, yet will be one of the most important.

As an example.  Imagine that someone rapes someone, or uses drugs to allow them to rape someone.  If the victim can “review” the person, and let others know that they were a victim of rape, this could be a significant deterrent.  If you are a woman, and someone offers to buy you a drink, and you can look up their profile and reputation and see that there are numerous “reviews” of rape, you are far more likely to be cautious around that person.

The reputation system, all by itself is a world changing event.  If an honest and non-biased system, with significant checks and balances could help determine a persons character, it could not only help make better informed decisions in dating, employment, and more, but it would encourage people to change for the better in order to increase their reputation.  It would encourage people to give more, share more, and be better people, because there was a way of tracking everything, they did that was good.  And on the converse, if everything bad, evil, and horrible that you did was recorded, it would encourage people refrain from evil

The entire reputation system is going to be the most controversial part of the Hypernet, yet the most powerful to create positive social change.  It will have as many checks and balances as society can come up with to make the system fair and have a sliding scale that punishes people most for recent infractions and forgives people for mistakes of the past, but it will encourage people to work for the greater good instead of selfish interests.

### Discussions and Voting {#discussions-and-voting}

The discussions and voting objects are one of the most critical to the success of the Hypernet.  It creates a completely new form of “education-based democracy” that has the capability of completely destroying fake news.

Any object or piece of information can be flagged by any user as “potentially untrue”.  In the Hypernet, this will create a new “discussions and voting” object that is attached to it.  As soon as information is flagged, there will be a yellow border around the object showing that it is under dispute.    
\<insert graphic showing flagged data\>

A “Discussions” object will be spawned and attached that allows users to debate the topic in an organized format that allows multiple viewpoints (not only pro, or con, but representing other sides).  A virtual debate is organized that allows for a discussion of the ideas in an organized format where every pro and con can be discussed  
\<insert graphic showing discussions, similar to Kiola\>

The Reputation System is applied to each topic discussed, to allow the Hypernet to color code all responses and let readers know just how knowledgeable a person is about a topic they are debating.  If it’s computer related, my name, as a computer specialist will show as one color, while another topic about botany my name will show as a different color, indicating that I’m not as knowledgeable in that subject.  As people browse the discussions, their levels of skill in any particular subject is apparent.  The color a users name appears in, shows you in a gradient, just how knowledgeable that person is in that subject.  This is INCREDIBLY powerful, because instead of the current systems where it’s impossible to know how knowledgeable someone is in a topic. The Hypernet immediately makes it visible how expert someone is in the topic.  This, all by itself, is a game changer.  
\<insert graphic

###### Voting system

Once a proper debate has occurred, the Object goes to a vote, for it’s truthfulness.

Unlike traditional voting systems that allow a one vote per person, the Hypernet is a Knowledge-based Democracy.  The greater your knowledge about the subject, the more votes you have.  This will take a lot of fine-tuning and finessing, admittedly.  But at it’s core, the Hypernet says that those who understand the subject they are voting for, the greater the weight their vote counts for.  So, as a hypothetical example, if a vote is called about an Object dealing with Quantum Physics, someone with a PHD in the field might find that their vote is worth 10x that of someone who is uneducated. (or more, the weights will need to be experimented with)

Although in some ways, this might seem unfair at face value, it helps to understand that everyone has their areas that they are expert at, and although one person might not have a high weight on Quantum Physics related subjects, they might have a higher vote on botany, chemistry, politics (or local politics), or more.

**This is one of the single most radical ideas about the Hypernet.  It is an informed, knowledge based democracy that helps the world discuss topics and see in the debates who actually knows what they are debating about, and gives those with more knowledge a weighted vote based on their level of knowledge.**

I cannot stress this enough.  The Hypernet will never fact-check or decide that it is the final judge of what is true or not.  It will ALWAYS use this advanced knowledge-based democracy to fact check and determine what is true.

This is one of the most important checks and balances on the system.  Any company/organization/etc that is allowed to determine what is true, is also subject to corruption.  Only an intelligent, democratic system can be the most possibly object system available.

And most importantly, once this advanced knowledge-based democracy is proven and the bugs worked out,, it will be used to run the Hypernet, and hopefully provide a platform for world governance that could change the world forever.
